
Make a list of the top ten security take aways - i.e., bullet points with brief descriptions
  If someone can persuade you to run their program on your computer, it's not
your computer anymore.
  If someone can alter the operating system on your computer all hope is lost.
  If someone can touch your computer it can be broken into.
  Weak passwords trump strong security.
  Absolute anonymity isn't practical, in real life or on the Web.
  Software products are not perfect.
  Crypto is hard.
  Hiding it doesn't secure it.
  The use of obscurity alone invites compromise.
  Proactive protection is needed.
Which of these is the least surprising? Why?
  If someone can touch your pc they can break into it.
  They can directly manipulate your hardware making it much easier to breach.
Which one of these is the most surprising (might the fewest people know)? Why?
  Hiding it doesn't secure it.
  They will find you.
